# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: content-security-policy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-default-src] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-default-src] It’s been available across browsers since August 2016.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-default-src] The HTTP `Content-Security-Policy` (CSP) **`default-src`** directive serves as a fallback for the other CSP fetch directives.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-default-src] A space-separated list of *source expression* values.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-default-src] Resources may be loaded if they match any of the given source expressions.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-default-src] For this directive, any of the source expression values listed in Fetch directive syntax are applicable.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-default-src] If there are other directives specified, `default-src` does not influence them.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-default-src] When creating a CSP, you can start with `default-src 'none'` to lock down all resource loading and then add further directives to open up the policy, allowing you to load just the resources you need.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-default-src] your SVG images will be blocked in Firefox if you have a `default-src 'none'` policy set.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-default-src] Firefox does not treat the SVG as an embedded image like other browsers do, therefore `img-src 'self'` will not allow them to be loaded.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-default-src] You need to use `default-src 'self'` if you want your external sprites to load in Firefox.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] The HTTP `Content-Security-Policy` (CSP) **`script-src`** directive specifies valid sources for JavaScript.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] This includes not only URLs loaded directly into `<script>` elements, but also things like inline script event handlers (`onclick`) and XSLT stylesheets which can trigger script execution.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] No resources of this type may be loaded.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] Resources of this type may be loaded if they match any of the given source expressions.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] If you cannot replace inline event handlers, you can use the `'unsafe-hashes'` source expression to allow them.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] Allowing trusted domains, as shown in the section above, is a broad-brushed approach for specifying the locations from which code can safely be loaded.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] This is a pragmatic approach, in particular when your site uses many resources and you have confidence that the trusted site will not be compromised.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] An alternative method is to specify allowed scripts using file hashes.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] Using this approach an external file in a `<script>` element can only be loaded and executed if all the valid hash values in its `integrity` attribute match the allowed values in the CSP header.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] The Subresource integrity feature additionally checks that the downloaded file has the indicated hash value, and therefore has not been modified.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] This is safer than trusting a domain, because files will only be used if they are unmodified, even if loaded from a compromised site.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] It is however more granular, and requires that hash values are updated in CSP and script elements whenever the associated scripts are changed.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] The CSP header below demonstrates the approach.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] It allows scripts for which the SHA384 hash is `oqVuAfXRKap7fdgcCY5uykM6+R9GqQ8K/uxy9rx7HNQlGYl1kPzQho1wx4JwY8wC` or the SHA256 hash is `fictional_value`.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] The `integrity` attribute can have multiple values, each providing a hash for the file calculated using a different algorithm.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] In order for an external script to be loaded, CSP requires that *all* valid hash values in the attribute must also be in the CSP `script-src` declaration.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] Therefore the script below would not load, because the second hash is not present in the CSP header above.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] This rule only applies to *valid* hash values.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] Subresource integrity contains more information about calculating hashes and using the `integrity` attribute.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] To allow inline scripts and styles, `'unsafe-inline'`, a nonce-source or a hash-source that matches the inline block can be specified.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] Allowing all inline scripts is considered a security risk, so it's recommended to use a nonce-source or a hash-source instead.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] To allow inline scripts and styles with a nonce-source, you need to generate a random nonce value (using a cryptographically secure random token generator) and include it in the policy.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] Alternatively, you can create hashes from your inline scripts.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] When generating the hash, don't include the `<script>` tags and note that capitalization and whitespace matter, including leading or trailing whitespace.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] Instead of allowing `'unsafe-inline'`, you can use the `'unsafe-hashes'` source expression if code can't be updated to equivalent `addEventListener` calls.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] The `'unsafe-eval'` source expression controls several script execution methods that create code from strings.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] The `'wasm-unsafe-eval'` source expression controls WebAssembly execution.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] If a page has a CSP header and `'wasm-unsafe-eval'` isn't specified in the `script-src` directive, WebAssembly is blocked from loading and executing on the page.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] The `'wasm-unsafe-eval'` source expression is more specific than `'unsafe-eval'` which permits both compilation (and instantiation) of WebAssembly and, for example, the use of the `eval` operation in JavaScript.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] If the `'unsafe-eval'` source keyword is used, then this overrides any occurrence of `'wasm-unsafe-eval'` in the CSP policy.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] The `'strict-dynamic'` source expression specifies that the trust explicitly given to a script present in the markup, by accompanying it with a nonce or a hash, shall be propagated to all the scripts loaded by that root script.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] At the same time, any allowlist or source expressions such as `'self'` or `'unsafe-inline'` will be ignored.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] It is possible to deploy `strict-dynamic` in a backwards compatible way, without requiring user-agent sniffing.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] will act like `'unsafe-inline' https:` in browsers that support CSP1, `https: 'nonce-abcdefg'` in browsers that support CSP2, and `'nonce-abcdefg' 'strict-dynamic'` in browsers that support CSP3.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy-script-src] To include speculation rules in a script element (see also `<script type="speculationrules">`), you need to use the `script-src` directive with one of the `'inline-speculation-rules'` source, a hash-source, or nonce-source.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy] The standard, originally named Content Restrictions, was proposed by Robert Hansen in 2004, first implemented in Firefox 4 and quickly picked up by other browsers.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy] Version 1 of the standard was published in 2012 as W3C candidate recommendation and quickly with further versions (Level 2) published in 2014.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy] As of 2023, the draft of Level 3 is being developed with the new features being quickly adopted by the web browsers.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy] A website can declare multiple CSP headers, also mixing enforcement and report-only ones.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy] Each header will be processed separately by the browser.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy] CSP can also be delivered within the HTML code using a meta tag, although in this case its effectiveness will be limited.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy] Internet Explorer 10 and Internet Explorer 11 also support CSP, but only sandbox directive, using the experimental `X-Content-Security-Policy` header.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy] A number of web application frameworks support CSP, for example AngularJS (natively) and Django (middleware).
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy] Instructions for Ruby on Rails have been posted by GitHub.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy] Web framework support is however only required if the CSP contents somehow depend on the web application's state—such as usage of the `nonce` origin.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy] Otherwise, the CSP is rather static and can be delivered from web application tiers above the application, for example on load balancer or web server.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy] In December 2015 and December 2016, a few methods of bypassing `'nonce'` allowlisting origins were published.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy] In January 2016, another method was published, which leverages server-wide CSP allowlisting to exploit old and vulnerable versions of JavaScript libraries hosted at the same server (frequent case with CDN servers).
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy] In May 2017 one more method was published to bypass CSP using web application frameworks code.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy] If the `Content-Security-Policy` header is present in the server response, a compliant client enforces the declarative allowlist policy.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy] One example goal of a policy is a stricter execution mode for JavaScript in order to prevent certain cross-site scripting attacks.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy] While using CSP in a new application may be quite straightforward, especially with CSP-compatible JavaScript framework, existing applications may require some refactoring—or relaxing the policy.
[src:content-security-policy/content-security-policy] Recommended coding practice for CSP-compatible web applications is to load code from external source files (`<script src>`), parse JSON instead of evaluating it and use `EventTarget.addEventListener()` to set event handlers.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] OWASP considers the term cross-site scripting to be a misnomer.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] It initially was an attack that was used for breaching data across sites, but gradually started to include other forms of data injection attacks.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Security on the web depends on a variety of mechanisms, including an underlying concept of trust known as the same-origin policy.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Content from URLs where any of these three attributes are different will have to be granted permissions separately.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting attacks use known vulnerabilities in web-based applications, their servers, or the plug-in systems on which they rely.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Exploiting one of these, attackers fold malicious content into the content being delivered from the compromised site.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] When the resulting combined content arrives at the client-side web browser, it has all been delivered from the trusted source, and thus operates under the permissions granted to that system.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] By finding ways of injecting malicious scripts into web pages, an attacker can gain elevated access-privileges to sensitive page content, to session cookies, and to a variety of other information maintained by the browser on behalf of the user.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting attacks are a case of code injection.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Microsoft security-engineers introduced the term "cross-site scripting" in January 2000.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] The definition gradually expanded to encompass other modes of code injection, including persistent and non-JavaScript vectors (including ActiveX, Java, VBScript, Flash, or even HTML scripts), causing some confusion to newcomers to the field of information security.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] XSS vulnerabilities have been reported and exploited since the 1990s.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Prominent sites affected in the past include the social-networking sites Twitter and Facebook.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting flaws have since surpassed buffer overflows to become the most common publicly reported security vulnerability, with some researchers in 2007 estimating as many as 68% of websites are likely open to XSS attacks.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] There is no single, standardized classification of cross-site scripting flaws, but most experts distinguish between at least two primary flavors of XSS flaws: *non-persistent* and *persistent*.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Some sources further divide these two groups into *traditional* (caused by server-side code flaws) and *DOM-based* (in client-side code).
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] The *non-persistent* (or *reflected*) cross-site scripting vulnerability is by far the most basic type of web vulnerability.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] These holes show up when the data provided by a web client, most commonly in HTTP query parameters (e.g.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] HTML form submission), is used immediately by server-side scripts to parse and display a page of results for that user, without properly sanitizing the content.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Because HTML documents have a flat, serial structure that mixes control statements, formatting, and the actual content, any non-validated user-supplied data included in the resulting page without proper HTML encoding, may lead to markup injection.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] A classic example of a potential vector is a site search engine: if one searches for a string, the search string will typically be redisplayed verbatim on the result page to indicate what was searched for.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] If this response does not properly escape or reject HTML control characters, a cross-site scripting flaw will ensue.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] A reflected attack is typically delivered via email or a neutral web site.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] The bait is an innocent-looking URL, pointing to a trusted site but containing the XSS vector.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] If the trusted site is vulnerable to the vector, clicking the link can cause the victim's browser to execute the injected script.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] A classic example of this is with online message boards where users are allowed to post HTML formatted messages for other users to read.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] For example, suppose there is a dating website where members scan the profiles of other members to see if they look interesting.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] For privacy reasons, this site hides everybody's real name and email.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] The only time a member's real name and email are in the browser is when the member is signed in, and they can't see anyone else's.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Suppose that Mallory, an attacker, joins the site and wants to figure out the real names of the people she sees on the site.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] To do so, she writes a script designed to run from other users' browsers when *they* visit *her* profile.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] The script then sends a quick message to her own server, which collects this information.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] To do this, for the question "Describe your Ideal First Date", Mallory gives a short answer (to appear normal), but the text at the end of her answer is her script to steal names and emails.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] If the script is enclosed inside a `<script>` element, it won't be shown on the screen.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Then suppose that Bob, a member of the dating site, reaches Mallory's profile, which has her answer to the First Date question.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Her script is run automatically by the browser and steals a copy of Bob's real name and email directly from his own machine.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Persistent XSS vulnerabilities can be more significant than other types because an attacker's malicious script is rendered automatically, without the need to individually target victims or lure them to a third-party website.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Particularly in the case of social networking sites, the code would be further designed to self-propagate across accounts, creating a type of client-side worm.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] The methods of injection can vary a great deal; in some cases, the attacker may not even need to directly interact with the web functionality itself to exploit such a hole.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Any data received by the web application (via email, system logs, IM etc.) that can be controlled by an attacker could become an injection vector.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] XSS vulnerabilities were originally found in applications that performed all data processing on the server side.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] User input (including an XSS vector) would be sent to the server, and then sent back to the user as a web page.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] The need for an improved user experience resulted in popularity of applications that had a majority of the presentation logic (maybe written in JavaScript) working on the client-side that pulled data, on-demand, from the server using AJAX.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] As the JavaScript code was also processing user input and rendering it in the web page content, a new sub-class of reflected XSS attacks started to appear that was called *DOM-based cross-site scripting*.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] In a DOM-based XSS attack, the malicious data does not touch the web server.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Rather, it is being reflected by the JavaScript code, fully on the client side.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] An example of a DOM-based XSS vulnerability is the bug found in 2011 in a number of jQuery plugins.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Prevention strategies for DOM-based XSS attacks include very similar measures to traditional XSS prevention strategies but implemented in JavaScript code and contained in web pages (i.e. input validation and escaping).
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Some JavaScript frameworks have built-in countermeasures against this and other types of attack — for example AngularJS.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Self-XSS is a form of XSS vulnerability that relies on social engineering in order to trick the victim into executing malicious JavaScript code in their browser.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Although it is technically not a true XSS vulnerability due to the fact it relies on socially engineering a user into executing code rather than a flaw in the affected website allowing an attacker to do so, it still poses the same risks as a regular XSS vulnerability if properly executed.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Mutated XSS happens when the attacker injects something that is seemingly safe but is rewritten and modified by the browser while parsing the markup.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] This makes it extremely hard to detect or sanitize within the website's application logic.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] An example is rebalancing unclosed quotation marks or even adding quotation marks to unquoted values in CSS font-family properties.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] There are several escaping schemes that can be used depending on where the untrusted string needs to be placed within an HTML document including HTML entity encoding, JavaScript escaping, CSS escaping, and URL (or percent) encoding.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Most web applications that do not need to accept rich data can use escaping to largely eliminate the risk of XSS attacks in a fairly straightforward manner.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Performing HTML entity encoding only on the five XML significant characters is not always sufficient to prevent many forms of XSS attacks, security encoding libraries are usually easier to use.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Some web template systems understand the structure of the HTML they produce and automatically pick an appropriate encoder.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Many operators of particular web applications (e.g. forums and webmail) allow users to utilize HTML markup.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] When accepting HTML input from users (say, `<b>very</b> large`), output encoding (such as `&lt;b&gt;very&lt;/b&gt; large`) will not suffice since the user input needs to be rendered as HTML by the browser (so it shows as `**very** large`, instead of `<b>very</b> large`).
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Stopping an XSS attack when accepting HTML input from users is much more complex in this situation.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Often, untrusted HTML input must be run through an HTML sanitization engine to ensure that it does not contain potentially malicious JavaScript code.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Many validations rely on parsing out (blacklisting) specific "at risk" HTML tags such as the `<iframe>`, `<link>`, and `<script>` tag, or by only allowing certain tags and removing or escaping others.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Another popular method is to strip user input of " and ' however this can also be bypassed as the payload can be concealed with obfuscation.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Besides content filtering, other imperfect methods for cross-site scripting mitigation are also commonly used.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] One example is the use of additional security controls when handling cookie-based user authentication.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Many web applications rely on session cookies for authentication between individual HTTP requests, and because client-side scripts generally have access to these cookies, simple XSS exploits can steal these cookies.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] To mitigate this particular threat (though not the XSS problem in general), many web applications tie session cookies to the IP address of the user who originally logged in, then only permit that IP to use that cookie.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] This is effective in most situations (if an attacker is only after the cookie), but obviously breaks down in situations where an attacker is behind the same NATed IP address or web proxy as the victim, or the victim is changing his or her mobile IP.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Another mitigation present in Internet Explorer (since version 6), Firefox (since version 2.0.0.5), Safari (since version 4), Opera (since version 9.5) and Google Chrome, is an *HttpOnly* flag which allows a web server to set a cookie that is unavailable to client-side scripts.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] While beneficial, the feature can neither fully prevent cookie theft nor prevent attacks within the browser.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] While Web 2.0 and Ajax developers require the use of JavaScript, some web applications are written to allow operation without the need for any client-side scripts.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] This allows users, if they choose, to disable scripting in their browsers before using the application.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] In this way, even potentially malicious client-side scripts could be inserted unescaped on a page, and users would not be susceptible to XSS attacks.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Some browsers or browser plugins can be configured to disable client-side scripts on a per-domain basis.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] This approach is of limited value if scripting is allowed by default, since it blocks bad sites only *after* the user knows that they are bad, which is too late.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Functionality that blocks all scripting and external inclusions by default and then allows the user to enable it on a per-domain basis is more effective.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] This has been possible for a long time in Internet Explorer (since version 4) by setting up its so called "Security Zones", and in Opera (since version 9) using its "Site Specific Preferences".
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] A solution for Firefox and other Gecko-based browsers is the open source NoScript add-on which, in addition to the ability to enable scripts on a per-domain basis, provides some XSS protection even when scripts are enabled.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Another problem with script blocking is that many users do not understand it, and do not know how to properly secure their browsers.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Yet another drawback is that many sites do not work without client-side scripting, forcing users to disable protection for that site and opening their systems to vulnerabilities.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] The Firefox NoScript extension enables users to allow scripts selectively from a given page while disallowing others on the same page.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] For example, scripts from example.com could be allowed, while scripts from advertisingagency.com that are attempting to run on the same page could be disallowed.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Trusted types changes Web APIs to check that values have been trademarked as trusted.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] As long as programs only trademark trustworthy values, an attacker who controls a JavaScript string value cannot cause XSS.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Trusted types are designed to be auditable by blue teams.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] Another defense approach is to use automated tools that will remove XSS malicious code in web pages, these tools use static analysis and/or pattern matching methods to identify malicious codes potentially and secure them using methods like escaping.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] When a cookie is set with the `SameSite=Strict` parameter, it is stripped from all cross-origin requests.
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] When set with `SameSite=Lax`, it is stripped from all non-"safe" cross-origin requests (that is, requests other than GET, OPTIONS, and TRACE which have read-only semantics).
[src:content-security-policy/cross-site-scripting] The feature is implemented in Google Chrome since version 63 and Firefox since version 60.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The primary use case for CSP is to control which resources, in particular JavaScript resources, a document is allowed to load.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] This is mainly used as a defense against cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks, in which an attacker is able to inject malicious code into the victim's site.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] A CSP can have other purposes as well, including defending against clickjacking and helping to ensure that a site's pages will be loaded over HTTPS.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] In this guide we'll start by describing how a CSP is delivered to a browser and what it looks like at a high level.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Restrict embedding, to protect against clickjacking.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Upgrade insecure requests, to help ensure that all resources are served over HTTPS.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Require the use of trusted types, to help defend against client-side XSS.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Note that there's no dependency between the different use cases: if you want to add clickjacking protection but not XSS mitigation, you can just add the directives for that use case.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Finally we'll describe strategies for deploying a CSP and tools that can help to make this process easier.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] A CSP should be delivered to the browser in the `Content-Security-Policy` response header.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] It should be set on all responses to all requests, not just the main document.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] You can also specify it using the `http-equiv` attribute of your document's `<meta>` element, and this is a useful option for some use cases, such as a client-side-rendered single page app which has only static resources, because you can then avoid relying on any server infrastructure.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] However, this option does not support all CSP features.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The policy is specified as a series of *directives*, separated by semi-colons.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Each directive controls a different aspect of the security policy.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Each directive has a name, followed by a space, followed by a value.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Different directives can have different syntaxes.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The first directive, `default-src`, tells the browser to load only resources that are same-origin with the document, unless other more specific directives set a different policy for other resource types.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The second, `img-src`, tells the browser to load images that are same-origin or that are served from `example.com`.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] In the next section, we'll look at the tools available to control resource loads, which is the main function of a CSP.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] A CSP can be used to control the resources that a document is allowed to load.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] This is primarily used for protection against cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] In this section we'll first see how controlling resource loads can help protect against XSS, then at the tools CSP provides to control what resources are loaded.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Finally we'll describe one particular recommended strategy, which is called a "Strict CSP".
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] A cross-site scripting (XSS) attack is one in which an attacker is able to execute their code in the context of the target website.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] An XSS attack is possible when a website accepts some input which might have been crafted by an attacker (for example, URL parameters, or a comment on a blog post) and then includes it in the page without *sanitizing* it: that is, without ensuring that it can't be executed as JavaScript.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Websites should protect themselves against XSS by sanitizing this input before including it in the page.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] By controlling resource loading, a CSP can provide protection against all of these.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] In the next section we'll go over the tools CSP provides to do these things.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Fetch directives are used to specify a particular category of resource that a document is allowed to load — such as JavaScript, CSS stylesheets, images, fonts, and so on.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] There are different fetch directives for different types of resource.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] One special fetch directive is `default-src`, which sets a fallback policy for all resources whose directives are not explicitly listed.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] For the complete set of fetch directives, see the reference documentation.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Each fetch directive is specified as either the single keyword `'none'` or one or more *source expressions*, separated by spaces.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] When more than one source expression is listed: if any of the methods allow the resource, then the resource is allowed.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] In the next few sections we'll describe some of the ways you can use source expressions to control resource loads.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Note that although we're describing them separately, these expressions can in general be combined: for example, a single fetch directive may include nonces as well as hostnames.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] To block a resource type entirely, use the `'none'` keyword.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Note that `'none'` cannot be combined with any other method in a particular directive: in practice, if any other source expressions are given alongside `'none'`, then they are ignored.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] A `nonce` is the recommended approach for restricting the loading of `<script>` and `<style>` resources.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The server then includes this value as the value of the `nonce` attribute of all the `<script>` and/or `<style>` tags that they intend to include in the document.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The browser compares the two values, and loads the resource only if they match.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The idea is that even if an attacker can insert some JavaScript into the page, they won't know which nonce the server is going to use, so the browser will refuse to run the script.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] For this approach to work, it must not be possible for an attacker to guess the nonce.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] This in turn means that the server cannot serve static HTML, because it must insert a new nonce each time.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Typically the server would use a templating engine to insert the nonce.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] On every request, the server generates a new nonce, inserts it into the CSP and into the `<script>` tags in the returned document.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] It's important that the server uses some kind of templating to insert nonces, and does not just insert them into all `<script>` tags: otherwise, the server might inadvertently insert nonces into scripts that were injected by an attacker.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Note that nonces can only be used for elements that have a `nonce` attribute: that is, only `<script>` and `<style>` elements.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Fetch directives can also use a hash of the script to guarantee its integrity.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] 3. appends a prefix identifying the hash algorithm used (one of `sha256-`, `sha384-`, or `sha512-`).
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] When the browser receives the document, it hashes the script, compares the result with the value from the header, and loads the script only if they match.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] External scripts must also include the `integrity` attribute for this method to work.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Fetch directives can list a scheme, like `https:`, to allow resources that are served using that scheme.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Fetch directives can control resource loads based on where the resource is located.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] You can also specify one or more hostnames, potentially including wildcards, and only resources served from those hosts will be allowed.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] This might be used, for example, to allow content to be served from a trusted CDN.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] If a CSP contains either a `default-src` or a `script-src` directive, then inline JavaScript will not be allowed to execute unless extra measures are taken to enable it.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The `unsafe-inline` keyword can be used to override this restriction.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Inline `<script>` elements are allowed if they are protected by a nonce or a hash, as described above.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] If a directive contains nonce or hash expressions, then the `unsafe-inline` keyword is ignored by browsers.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Like inline JavaScript, if a CSP contains either a `default-src` or a `script-src` directive, then `eval()` and similar APIs will not be allowed to execute.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The `unsafe-eval` keyword can be used to override this behavior, and as with `unsafe-inline`, and for the same reasons: **developers should avoid `unsafe-eval`**.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Sometimes it can be difficult to remove usages of `eval()` and the other methods: in these situations, the Trusted Types API can make it safer, by ensuring that the input meets a defined policy.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The `trusted-types-eval` keyword should be used to override the behavior in this case.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Unlike `unsafe-inline` it only overrides the behavior in browser when trusted types are supported and enabled; which ensures that the methods will remain blocked on browsers that don't support trusted types.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Unlike `unsafe-inline`, the `unsafe-eval` keyword does still work in a directive that contains nonce or hash expressions.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] To control script loading as a mitigation against XSS, recommended practice is to use nonce- or hash- based fetch directives.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Nonce-based directives are easier to maintain if you can generate responses, including the content itself, dynamically.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Otherwise, you need to use hash-based directives.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The problem with hash-based directives is that you need to recalculate and reapply the hash if any change is made to the script contents.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] As presented above, the strict CSP is difficult to implement when you use scripts which are not under your control.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] If a third-party script loads any additional scripts, or uses any inline scripts, then this will fail, because the third-party script won't pass the nonce or hash through.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The `strict-dynamic` keyword is provided to help with this problem.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] It is a keyword that can be included in a fetch directive, and it has the effect that if a script has a nonce or a hash attached to it, then that script will be allowed to load further scripts which do not themselves have nonces or hashes.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] That is, the trust placed in a script by a nonce or hash is passed on to scripts that the original script loads (and scripts that *they* load, and so on).
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The "main.js" script will be allowed to load, because its hash matches the value in the CSP.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] But its attempt to load "main2.js" will fail.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The `'strict-dynamic'` keyword makes it much easier to create and maintain nonce- or hash-based CSPs, especially when a website uses third-party scripts.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] It does make your CSP less secure, though, because if the scripts you include create `<script>` elements based on potential sources of XSS, then the CSP will not protect them.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] We've seen above that inline JavaScript is disallowed by default in a CSP.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] With nonces or hashes, a developer can use inline `<script>` tags, but you'll still need to refactor code to remove other disallowed patterns, including inline event handlers, `javascript:` URLs, and uses of `eval()`.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The `frame-ancestors` directive can be used to control which documents, if any, are allowed to embed this document in a nested browsing context such as an `<iframe>`.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] This is an effective protection against clickjacking attacks, because these attacks depend on embedding the target site in a site controlled by the attacker.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The syntax of `frame-ancestors` is a subset of the fetch directive syntax: you can provide the single keyword value `'none'` or one or more source expressions.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] However, the only source expressions you can use are schemes, hostnames, or the `'self'` keyword value.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] This directive is a more flexible replacement for the `X-Frame-Options` header.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Web developers are strongly encouraged to serve all their content over HTTPS.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] This is called *mixed content*, and the presence of insecure resources greatly weakens the protection afforded by HTTPS.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Under the mixed content algorithm that browsers implement, if a document is served over HTTPS, insecure resources are categorized into "upgradable content" and "blockable content".
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Upgradable content is upgraded to HTTPS, and blockable content is blocked, potentially breaking the page.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The ultimate solution to mixed content is for developers to load all resources over HTTPS.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] However, even if a site is actually able to serve all content over HTTPS, it can still be very difficult (or even effectively impossible, where archived content is concerned) for a developer to rewrite all the URLs the site uses to load resources.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The `upgrade-insecure-requests` directive is intended to solve this problem.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] However, top-level navigation requests whose target is a different origin will not be upgraded.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The browser will automatically upgrade both of these requests to HTTPS.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The browser will upgrade the first link to HTTPS, but not the second, as it is navigating to a different origin.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] This directive is not a substitute for the `Strict-Transport-Security` header (also known as HSTS), because it does not upgrade external links to a site.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Sites should include this directive and the `Strict-Transport-Security` header.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The `require-trusted-types-for` and `trusted-types` directives can be used to enforce the Trusted Types API.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] This allows you to defend against client-side cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks by mandating that any input must be passed through a transformation function, providing an opportunity to make it safe before it is sent to a web platform API that might otherwise execute it as code.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Some APIs in the web platform are known as *injection sinks*.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] These are APIs that can be passed some input, usually in the form of a string, and that can interpret that input as code.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] In this guide we've already seen `eval()`, but there are many other injection sinks, such as `Element.innerHTML` or `Document.write()`.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] If an attacker can supply some specially crafted input to your website, and your website passes it to one of these injection sinks, then the attacker can execute malicious code.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Some injection sinks, like `eval()`, are very hard to use safely, and we've seen that a CSP will typically block them entirely.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Others can be made safer if the input to them is processed so as to remove unsafe elements.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] With the Trusted Types API, you can pass *trusted types* into injection sinks, instead of strings.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Trusted types are objects that result from passing potentially dangerous input through a transformation function.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] This transformation typically sanitizes the input, by removing any elements that might make it executable (such as `<script>` tags).
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] By default, your code could choose to pass trusted types or unsanitized strings to injection sinks.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] However, if you include the `require-trusted-types-for` directive in your CSP, and give it a value of `'script'`, then the browser will only allow your site to pass trusted types to injection sinks.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Trusted type objects are created using a user-defined *policy* object.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Your code can create any kind of policy object, including ones whose transformation function doesn't actually sanitize the input, and therefore doesn't protect you.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] To minimize this risk, you can include the `trusted-types` directive.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] This lists the names of acceptable policies, and the browser will only allow those named policies to be used.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] To ease deployment, CSP can be deployed in report-only mode.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The policy is not enforced, but any violations are sent to the reporting endpoint specified in the policy.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Additionally, a report-only header can be used to test a future revision to a policy without actually deploying it.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] If both a `Content-Security-Policy-Report-Only` header and a `Content-Security-Policy` header are present in the same response, both policies are honored.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The policy specified in `Content-Security-Policy` headers is enforced while the `Content-Security-Policy-Report-Only` policy generates reports but is not enforced.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] Note that unlike a normal content security policy, a report-only policy cannot be delivered in a `<meta>` element.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The recommended method for reporting CSP violations is to use the Reporting API, declaring endpoints in `Reporting-Endpoints` and specifying one of them as the CSP reporting target using the `Content-Security-Policy` header's `report-to` directive.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] A server can inform clients where to send reports using the `Reporting-Endpoints` HTTP response header.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] This header defines one or more endpoint URLs as a comma-separated list.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] You can then use the `Content-Security-Policy` header's `report-to` directive to specify that a particular defined endpoint should be used for reporting.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] When a CSP violation occurs, the browser sends the report as a JSON object to the specified endpoint via an HTTP `POST` operation, with a `Content-Type` of `application/reports+json`.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The report is a serialized form of the `CSPViolationReport` object containing a `type` property with a value of `"csp-violation"`.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] You need to set up a server to receive reports with the given JSON format and content type.
[src:content-security-policy/guides-csp] The server handling these requests can then store or process the incoming reports in a way that best suits your needs.
